4324 bool Assembler::IsImmLLiteral(int64_t offset) {
4325  int inst_size = static_cast<int>(kInstrSizeLog2);
4326  bool offset_is_inst_multiple =
4327  (static_cast<int64_t>(static_cast<uint64_t>(offset >> inst_size)
4328  << inst_size) == offset);
4329  DCHECK_GT(offset, 0);
4330  offset >>= kLoadLiteralScaleLog2;
4331  return offset_is_inst_multiple && is_intn(offset, ImmLLiteral_width);
4332 }
4333 
4334 // Test if a given value can be encoded in the immediate field of a logical
4335 // instruction.
4336 // If it can be encoded, the function returns true, and values pointed to by n,
4337 // imm_s and imm_r are updated with immediates encoded in the format required
4338 // by the corresponding fields in the logical instruction.
4339 // If it can not be encoded, the function returns false, and the values pointed
4340 // to by n, imm_s and imm_r are undefined.
4341 bool Assembler::IsImmLogical(uint64_t value, unsigned width, unsigned* n,
4342  unsigned* imm_s, unsigned* imm_r) {
4343  DCHECK((n != nullptr) && (imm_s != nullptr) && (imm_r != nullptr));
4344  DCHECK((width == kWRegSizeInBits) || (width == kXRegSizeInBits));
4345 
4346  bool negate = false;
4347 
4348  // Logical immediates are encoded using parameters n, imm_s and imm_r using
4349  // the following table:
4350  //
4351  // N imms immr size S R
4352  // 1 ssssss rrrrrr 64 UInt(ssssss) UInt(rrrrrr)
4353  // 0 0sssss xrrrrr 32 UInt(sssss) UInt(rrrrr)
4354  // 0 10ssss xxrrrr 16 UInt(ssss) UInt(rrrr)
4355  // 0 110sss xxxrrr 8 UInt(sss) UInt(rrr)
4356  // 0 1110ss xxxxrr 4 UInt(ss) UInt(rr)
4357  // 0 11110s xxxxxr 2 UInt(s) UInt(r)
4358  // (s bits must not be all set)
4359  //
4360  // A pattern is constructed of size bits, where the least significant S+1 bits
4361  // are set. The pattern is rotated right by R, and repeated across a 32 or
4362  // 64-bit value, depending on destination register width.
4363  //
4364  // Put another way: the basic format of a logical immediate is a single
4365  // contiguous stretch of 1 bits, repeated across the whole word at intervals
4366  // given by a power of 2. To identify them quickly, we first locate the
4367  // lowest stretch of 1 bits, then the next 1 bit above that; that combination
4368  // is different for every logical immediate, so it gives us all the
4369  // information we need to identify the only logical immediate that our input
4370  // could be, and then we simply check if that's the value we actually have.
4371  //
4372  // (The rotation parameter does give the possibility of the stretch of 1 bits
4373  // going 'round the end' of the word. To deal with that, we observe that in
4374  // any situation where that happens the bitwise NOT of the value is also a
4375  // valid logical immediate. So we simply invert the input whenever its low bit
4376  // is set, and then we know that the rotated case can't arise.)
4377 
4378  if (value & 1) {
4379  // If the low bit is 1, negate the value, and set a flag to remember that we
4380  // did (so that we can adjust the return values appropriately).
4381  negate = true;
4382  value = ~value;
4383  }
4384 
4385  if (width == kWRegSizeInBits) {
4386  // To handle 32-bit logical immediates, the very easiest thing is to repeat
4387  // the input value twice to make a 64-bit word. The correct encoding of that
4388  // as a logical immediate will also be the correct encoding of the 32-bit
4389  // value.
4390 
4391  // The most-significant 32 bits may not be zero (ie. negate is true) so
4392  // shift the value left before duplicating it.
4393  value <<= kWRegSizeInBits;
4394  value |= value >> kWRegSizeInBits;
4395  }
4396 
4397  // The basic analysis idea: imagine our input word looks like this.
4398  //
4399  // 0011111000111110001111100011111000111110001111100011111000111110
4400  // c b a
4401  // |<--d-->|
4402  //
4403  // We find the lowest set bit (as an actual power-of-2 value, not its index)
4404  // and call it a. Then we add a to our original number, which wipes out the
4405  // bottommost stretch of set bits and replaces it with a 1 carried into the
4406  // next zero bit. Then we look for the new lowest set bit, which is in
4407  // position b, and subtract it, so now our number is just like the original
4408  // but with the lowest stretch of set bits completely gone. Now we find the
4409  // lowest set bit again, which is position c in the diagram above. Then we'll
4410  // measure the distance d between bit positions a and c (using CLZ), and that
4411  // tells us that the only valid logical immediate that could possibly be equal
4412  // to this number is the one in which a stretch of bits running from a to just
4413  // below b is replicated every d bits.
4414  uint64_t a = LargestPowerOf2Divisor(value);
4415  uint64_t value_plus_a = value + a;
4416  uint64_t b = LargestPowerOf2Divisor(value_plus_a);
4417  uint64_t value_plus_a_minus_b = value_plus_a - b;
4418  uint64_t c = LargestPowerOf2Divisor(value_plus_a_minus_b);
4419 
4420  int d, clz_a, out_n;
4421  uint64_t mask;
4422 
4423  if (c != 0) {
4424  // The general case, in which there is more than one stretch of set bits.
4425  // Compute the repeat distance d, and set up a bitmask covering the basic
4426  // unit of repetition (i.e. a word with the bottom d bits set). Also, in all
4427  // of these cases the N bit of the output will be zero.
4428  clz_a = CountLeadingZeros(a, kXRegSizeInBits);
4429  int clz_c = CountLeadingZeros(c, kXRegSizeInBits);
4430  d = clz_a - clz_c;
4431  mask = ((uint64_t{1} << d) - 1);
4432  out_n = 0;
4433  } else {
4434  // Handle degenerate cases.
4435  //
4436  // If any of those 'find lowest set bit' operations didn't find a set bit at
4437  // all, then the word will have been zero thereafter, so in particular the
4438  // last lowest_set_bit operation will have returned zero. So we can test for
4439  // all the special case conditions in one go by seeing if c is zero.
4440  if (a == 0) {
4441  // The input was zero (or all 1 bits, which will come to here too after we
4442  // inverted it at the start of the function), for which we just return
4443  // false.
4444  return false;
4445  } else {
4446  // Otherwise, if c was zero but a was not, then there's just one stretch
4447  // of set bits in our word, meaning that we have the trivial case of
4448  // d == 64 and only one 'repetition'. Set up all the same variables as in
4449  // the general case above, and set the N bit in the output.
4450  clz_a = CountLeadingZeros(a, kXRegSizeInBits);
4451  d = 64;
4452  mask = ~uint64_t{0};
4453  out_n = 1;
4454  }
4455  }
4456 
4457  // If the repeat period d is not a power of two, it can't be encoded.
4458  if (!base::bits::IsPowerOfTwo(d)) {
4459  return false;
4460  }
4461 
4462  if (((b - a) & ~mask) != 0) {
4463  // If the bit stretch (b - a) does not fit within the mask derived from the
4464  // repeat period, then fail.
4465  return false;
4466  }
4467 
4468  // The only possible option is b - a repeated every d bits. Now we're going to
4469  // actually construct the valid logical immediate derived from that
4470  // specification, and see if it equals our original input.
4471  //
4472  // To repeat a value every d bits, we multiply it by a number of the form
4473  // (1 + 2^d + 2^(2d) + ...), i.e. 0x0001000100010001 or similar. These can
4474  // be derived using a table lookup on CLZ(d).
4475  static const uint64_t multipliers[] = {
4476  0x0000000000000001UL, 0x0000000100000001UL, 0x0001000100010001UL,
4477  0x0101010101010101UL, 0x1111111111111111UL, 0x5555555555555555UL,
4478  };
4479  int multiplier_idx = CountLeadingZeros(d, kXRegSizeInBits) - 57;
4480  // Ensure that the index to the multipliers array is within bounds.
4481  DCHECK((multiplier_idx >= 0) &&
4482  (static_cast<size_t>(multiplier_idx) < arraysize(multipliers)));
4483  uint64_t multiplier = multipliers[multiplier_idx];
4484  uint64_t candidate = (b - a) * multiplier;
4485 
4486  if (value != candidate) {
4487  // The candidate pattern doesn't match our input value, so fail.
4488  return false;
4489  }
4490 
4491  // We have a match! This is a valid logical immediate, so now we have to
4492  // construct the bits and pieces of the instruction encoding that generates
4493  // it.
4494 
4495  // Count the set bits in our basic stretch. The special case of clz(0) == -1
4496  // makes the answer come out right for stretches that reach the very top of
4497  // the word (e.g. numbers like 0xFFFFC00000000000).
4498  int clz_b = (b == 0) ? -1 : CountLeadingZeros(b, kXRegSizeInBits);
4499  int s = clz_a - clz_b;
4500 
4501  // Decide how many bits to rotate right by, to put the low bit of that basic
4502  // stretch in position a.
4503  int r;
4504  if (negate) {
4505  // If we inverted the input right at the start of this function, here's
4506  // where we compensate: the number of set bits becomes the number of clear
4507  // bits, and the rotation count is based on position b rather than position
4508  // a (since b is the location of the 'lowest' 1 bit after inversion).
4509  s = d - s;
4510  r = (clz_b + 1) & (d - 1);
4511  } else {
4512  r = (clz_a + 1) & (d - 1);
4513  }
4514 
4515  // Now we're done, except for having to encode the S output in such a way that
4516  // it gives both the number of set bits and the length of the repeated
4517  // segment. The s field is encoded like this:
4518  //
4519  // imms size S
4520  // ssssss 64 UInt(ssssss)
4521  // 0sssss 32 UInt(sssss)
4522  // 10ssss 16 UInt(ssss)
4523  // 110sss 8 UInt(sss)
4524  // 1110ss 4 UInt(ss)
4525  // 11110s 2 UInt(s)
4526  //
4527  // So we 'or' (-d * 2) with our computed s to form imms.
4528  *n = out_n;
4529  *imm_s = ((-d * 2) | (s - 1)) & 0x3F;
4530  *imm_r = r;
4531 
4532  return true;
4533 }
4534 
4535 bool Assembler::IsImmFP32(uint32_t bits) {
4536  // Valid values will have the form:
4537  // aBbb.bbbc.defg.h000.0000.0000.0000.0000
4538  // bits[19..0] are cleared.
4539  if ((bits & 0x7FFFF) != 0) {
4540  return false;
4541  }
4542 
4543  // bits[29..25] are all set or all cleared.
4544  uint32_t b_pattern = (bits >> 16) & 0x3E00;
4545  if (b_pattern != 0 && b_pattern != 0x3E00) {
4546  return false;
4547  }
4548 
4549  // bit[30] and bit[29] are opposite.
4550  if (((bits ^ (bits << 1)) & 0x40000000) == 0) {
4551  return false;
4552  }
4553 
4554  return true;
4555 }
4556 
4557 bool Assembler::IsImmFP64(uint64_t bits) {
4558  // Valid values will have the form:
4559  // aBbb.bbbb.bbcd.efgh.0000.0000.0000.0000
4560  // 0000.0000.0000.0000.0000.0000.0000.0000
4561  // bits[47..0] are cleared.
4562  if ((bits & 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFL) != 0) {
4563  return false;
4564  }
4565 
4566  // bits[61..54] are all set or all cleared.
4567  uint32_t b_pattern = (bits >> 48) & 0x3FC0;
4568  if (b_pattern != 0 && b_pattern != 0x3FC0) {
4569  return false;
4570  }
4571 
4572  // bit[62] and bit[61] are opposite.
4573  if (((bits ^ (bits << 1)) & 0x4000000000000000L) == 0) {
4574  return false;
4575  }
4576 
4577  return true;
4578 }
4579 
4580 void Assembler::GrowBuffer() {
4581  // Compute new buffer size.
4582  int old_size = buffer_->size();
4583  int new_size = std::min(2 * old_size, old_size + 1 * MB);
4584 
4585  // Some internal data structures overflow for very large buffers,
4586  // they must ensure that kMaximalBufferSize is not too large.
4587  if (new_size > kMaximalBufferSize) {
4588  V8::FatalProcessOutOfMemory(nullptr, "Assembler::GrowBuffer");
4589  }
4590 
4591  // Set up new buffer.
4592  std::unique_ptr<AssemblerBuffer> new_buffer = buffer_->Grow(new_size);
4593  DCHECK_EQ(new_size, new_buffer->size());
4594  uint8_t* new_start = new_buffer->start();
4595 
4596  // Copy the data.
4597  intptr_t pc_delta = new_start - buffer_start_;
4598  intptr_t rc_delta = (new_start + new_size) - (buffer_start_ + old_size);
4599  size_t reloc_size = (buffer_start_ + old_size) - reloc_info_writer.pos();
4600  memmove(new_start, buffer_start_, pc_offset());
4601  memmove(reloc_info_writer.pos() + rc_delta, reloc_info_writer.pos(),
4602  reloc_size);
4603 
4604  // Switch buffers.
4605  buffer_ = std::move(new_buffer);
4606  buffer_start_ = new_start;
4607  pc_ += pc_delta;
4608  reloc_info_writer.Reposition(reloc_info_writer.pos() + rc_delta,
4609  reloc_info_writer.last_pc() + pc_delta);
4610 
4611  // None of our relocation types are pc relative pointing outside the code
4612  // buffer nor pc absolute pointing inside the code buffer, so there is no need
4613  // to relocate any emitted relocation entries.
4614 
4615  // Relocate internal references.
4616  for (auto pos : internal_reference_positions_) {
4617  Address address = reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(buffer_start_) + pos;
4618  intptr_t internal_ref = ReadUnalignedValue<intptr_t>(address);
4619  internal_ref += pc_delta;
4620  WriteUnalignedValue<intptr_t>(address, internal_ref);
4621  }
4622 
4623  // Pending relocation entries are also relative, no need to relocate.
4624 }
4625 
4626 void Assembler::RecordRelocInfo(RelocInfo::Mode rmode, intptr_t data,
4627  ConstantPoolMode constant_pool_mode) {
4628  if (rmode == RelocInfo::INTERNAL_REFERENCE ||
4629  rmode == RelocInfo::CONST_POOL || rmode == RelocInfo::VENEER_POOL ||
4630  rmode == RelocInfo::DEOPT_SCRIPT_OFFSET ||
4631  rmode == RelocInfo::DEOPT_INLINING_ID ||
4632  rmode == RelocInfo::DEOPT_REASON || rmode == RelocInfo::DEOPT_ID ||
4633  rmode == RelocInfo::DEOPT_NODE_ID) {
4634  // Adjust code for new modes.
4635  DCHECK(RelocInfo::IsDeoptReason(rmode) || RelocInfo::IsDeoptId(rmode) ||
4636  RelocInfo::IsDeoptNodeId(rmode) ||
4637  RelocInfo::IsDeoptPosition(rmode) ||
4638  RelocInfo::IsInternalReference(rmode) ||
4639  RelocInfo::IsConstPool(rmode) || RelocInfo::IsVeneerPool(rmode));
4640  // These modes do not need an entry in the constant pool.
4641  } else if (constant_pool_mode == NEEDS_POOL_ENTRY) {
4642  if (RelocInfo::IsEmbeddedObjectMode(rmode)) {
4643  Handle<HeapObject> handle(reinterpret_cast<Address*>(data));
4644  data = AddEmbeddedObject(handle);
4645  }
4646  if (rmode == RelocInfo::COMPRESSED_EMBEDDED_OBJECT) {
4647  if (constpool_.RecordEntry(static_cast<uint32_t>(data), rmode) ==
4648  RelocInfoStatus::kMustOmitForDuplicate) {
4649  return;
4650  }
4651  } else {
4652  if (constpool_.RecordEntry(static_cast<uint64_t>(data), rmode) ==
4653  RelocInfoStatus::kMustOmitForDuplicate) {
4654  return;
4655  }
4656  }
4657  }
4658  // For modes that cannot use the constant pool, a different sequence of
4659  // instructions will be emitted by this function's caller.
4660 
4661  if (!ShouldRecordRelocInfo(rmode)) return;
4662 
4663  // Callers should ensure that constant pool emission is blocked until the
4664  // instruction the reloc info is associated with has been emitted.
4665  DCHECK(constpool_.IsBlocked());
4666 
4667  // We do not try to reuse pool constants.
4668  RelocInfo rinfo(reinterpret_cast<Address>(pc_), rmode, data);
4669  DCHECK_GE(buffer_space(), kMaxRelocSize); // too late to grow buffer here
4670  reloc_info_writer.Write(&rinfo);
4671 }
4672 
4673 void Assembler::near_jump(int offset, RelocInfo::Mode rmode) {
4674  BlockPoolsScope no_pool_before_b_instr(this);
4675  if (!RelocInfo::IsNoInfo(rmode))
4676  RecordRelocInfo(rmode, offset, NO_POOL_ENTRY);
4677  b(offset);
4678 }

4680 void Assembler::near_call(int offset, RelocInfo::Mode rmode) {

4682  if (!RelocInfo::IsNoInfo(rmode))
4683  RecordRelocInfo(rmode, offset, NO_POOL_ENTRY);
4684  bl(offset);

4698 void ConstantPool::EmitPrologue(Alignment require_alignment) {
4699  // Recorded constant pool size is expressed in number of 32-bits words,
4700  // and includes prologue and alignment, but not the jump around the pool
4701  // and the size of the marker itself.
4702  const int marker_size = 1;
4703  int word_count =
4704  ComputeSize(Jump::kOmitted, require_alignment) / kInt32Size - marker_size;
4705  assm_->Emit(LDR_x_lit | Assembler::ImmLLiteral(word_count) |
4706  Assembler::Rt(xzr));
4707  assm_->EmitPoolGuard();
4708 }
4709 
4710 int ConstantPool::PrologueSize(Jump require_jump) const {
4711  // Prologue is:
4712  // b over ;; if require_jump
4713  // ldr xzr, #pool_size
4714  // blr xzr
4715  int prologue_size = require_jump == Jump::kRequired ? kInstrSize : 0;
4716  prologue_size += 2 * kInstrSize;
4717  return prologue_size;
4718 }

4720 void ConstantPool::SetLoadOffsetToConstPoolEntry(int load_offset,
4721  Instruction* entry_offset,
4722  const ConstantPoolKey& key) {
4723  Instruction* instr = assm_->InstructionAt(load_offset);
4724  // Instruction to patch must be 'ldr rd, [pc, #offset]' with offset == 0.
4725  DCHECK(instr->IsLdrLiteral() && instr->ImmLLiteral() == 0);
4726  instr->SetImmPCOffsetTarget(assm_->zone(), assm_->options(), entry_offset);
4727 }
4728 
4729 void ConstantPool::Check(Emission force_emit, Jump require_jump,
4730  size_t margin) {
4731  // Some short sequence of instruction must not be broken up by constant pool
4732  // emission, such sequences are protected by a ConstPool::BlockScope.
4733  if (IsBlocked()) {
4734  // Something is wrong if emission is forced and blocked at the same time.
4735  DCHECK_EQ(force_emit, Emission::kIfNeeded);
4736  return;
4737  }
4738 
4739  // We emit a constant pool only if :
4740  // * it is not empty
4741  // * emission is forced by parameter force_emit (e.g. at function end).
4742  // * emission is mandatory or opportune according to {ShouldEmitNow}.
4743  if (!IsEmpty() && (force_emit == Emission::kForced ||
4744  ShouldEmitNow(require_jump, margin))) {
4745  // Emit veneers for branches that would go out of range during emission of
4746  // the constant pool.
4747  int worst_case_size = ComputeSize(Jump::kRequired, Alignment::kRequired);
4748  assm_->CheckVeneerPool(false, require_jump == Jump::kRequired,
4749  assm_->kVeneerDistanceMargin + worst_case_size +
4750  static_cast<int>(margin));
4751 
4752  // Check that the code buffer is large enough before emitting the constant
4753  // pool (this includes the gap to the relocation information).
4754  int needed_space = worst_case_size + assm_->kGap;
4755  while (assm_->buffer_space() <= needed_space) {
4756  assm_->GrowBuffer();
4757  }
4758 
4759  EmitAndClear(require_jump);
4760  }
4761  // Since a constant pool is (now) empty, move the check offset forward by
4762  // the standard interval.
4763  SetNextCheckIn(ConstantPool::kCheckInterval);
4764 }
4765 
4766 // Pool entries are accessed with pc relative load therefore this cannot be more
4767 // than 1 * MB. Since constant pool emission checks are interval based, and we
4768 // want to keep entries close to the code, we try to emit every 64KB.
4769 const size_t ConstantPool::kMaxDistToPool32 = 1 * MB;
4770 const size_t ConstantPool::kMaxDistToPool64 = 1 * MB;
4771 const size_t ConstantPool::kCheckInterval = 128 * kInstrSize;
4772 const size_t ConstantPool::kApproxDistToPool32 = 64 * KB;
4773 const size_t ConstantPool::kApproxDistToPool64 = kApproxDistToPool32;
4774 
4775 const size_t ConstantPool::kOpportunityDistToPool32 = 64 * KB;
4776 const size_t ConstantPool::kOpportunityDistToPool64 = 64 * KB;
4777 const size_t ConstantPool::kApproxMaxEntryCount = 512;
4778 
4779 intptr_t Assembler::MaxPCOffsetAfterVeneerPoolIfEmittedNow(size_t margin) {
4780  // Account for the branch and guard around the veneers.
4781  static constexpr int kBranchSizeInBytes = kInstrSize;
4782  static constexpr int kGuardSizeInBytes = kInstrSize;
4783  const size_t max_veneer_size_in_bytes =
4784  unresolved_branches_.size() * kVeneerCodeSize;
4785  return static_cast<intptr_t>(pc_offset() + kBranchSizeInBytes +
4786  kGuardSizeInBytes + max_veneer_size_in_bytes +
4787  margin);
4788 }
4789 
4790 void Assembler::RecordVeneerPool(int location_offset, int size) {
4791  Assembler::BlockPoolsScope block_pools(this, PoolEmissionCheck::kSkip);
4792  RelocInfo rinfo(reinterpret_cast<Address>(buffer_start_) + location_offset,
4793  RelocInfo::VENEER_POOL, static_cast<intptr_t>(size));
4794  reloc_info_writer.Write(&rinfo);
4795 }
4796 
4797 void Assembler::EmitVeneers(bool force_emit, bool need_protection,
4798  size_t margin) {
4799  ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4800  BlockPoolsScope scope(this, PoolEmissionCheck::kSkip);
4801 
4802  // The exact size of the veneer pool must be recorded (see the comment at the
4803  // declaration site of RecordConstPool()), but computing the number of
4804  // veneers that will be generated is not obvious. So instead we remember the
4805  // current position and will record the size after the pool has been
4806  // generated.
4807  Label size_check;
4808  bind(&size_check);
4809  int veneer_pool_relocinfo_loc = pc_offset();
4810 
4811  Label end;
4812  if (need_protection) {
4813  b(&end);
4814  }
4815 
4816  EmitVeneersGuard();
4817 
4818  // We only emit veneers if needed (unless emission is forced), i.e. when the
4819  // max-reachable-pc of the branch has been exhausted by the current codegen
4820  // state. Specifically, we emit when the max-reachable-pc of the branch <= the
4821  // max-pc-after-veneers (over-approximated).
4822  const intptr_t max_pc_after_veneers =
4823  MaxPCOffsetAfterVeneerPoolIfEmittedNow(margin);
4824 
4825  {
4826  // The `unresolved_branches_` map is sorted by max-reachable-pc in ascending
4827  // order.
4828  auto it = unresolved_branches_.begin();
4829  while (it != unresolved_branches_.end()) {
4830  const int max_reachable_pc = it->first & ~1;
4831  if (!force_emit && max_reachable_pc > max_pc_after_veneers) break;
4832 
4833  // Found a task. We'll emit a veneer for this.
4834 
4835  // Calculate the branch location from the maximum reachable PC. Only
4836  // B.cond, CB[N]Z and TB[N]Z are veneered, and the first two branch types
4837  // have the same range. The LSB (branch type tag bit) is set for TB[N]Z,
4838  // clear otherwise.
4839  int pc_offset = it->first;
4840  if (pc_offset & 1) {
4841  pc_offset -= (Instruction::ImmBranchRange(TestBranchType) + 1);
4842  } else {
4843  static_assert(Instruction::ImmBranchRange(CondBranchType) ==
4844  Instruction::ImmBranchRange(CompareBranchType));
4845  pc_offset -= Instruction::ImmBranchRange(CondBranchType);
4846  }
4847 #ifdef DEBUG
4848  Label veneer_size_check;
4849  bind(&veneer_size_check);
4850 #endif
4851  Label* label = it->second;
4852  Instruction* veneer = reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(pc_);
4853  Instruction* branch = InstructionAt(pc_offset);
4854  RemoveBranchFromLabelLinkChain(branch, label, veneer);
4855  branch->SetImmPCOffsetTarget(zone(), options(), veneer);
4856  b(label); // This may end up pointing at yet another veneer later on.
4857  DCHECK_EQ(SizeOfCodeGeneratedSince(&veneer_size_check),
4858  static_cast<uint64_t>(kVeneerCodeSize));
4859  it = unresolved_branches_.erase(it);
4860  }
4861  }
4862 
4863  // Update next_veneer_pool_check_ (tightly coupled with unresolved_branches_).
4864  // This must happen after the calls to {RemoveBranchFromLabelLinkChain},
4865  // because that function can resolve additional branches.
4866  if (unresolved_branches_.empty()) {
4867  next_veneer_pool_check_ = kMaxInt;
4868  } else {
4869  next_veneer_pool_check_ =
4870  unresolved_branches_first_limit() - kVeneerDistanceCheckMargin;
4871  }
4872 
4873  // Record the veneer pool size.
4874  int pool_size = static_cast<int>(SizeOfCodeGeneratedSince(&size_check));
4875  RecordVeneerPool(veneer_pool_relocinfo_loc, pool_size);
4876 
4877  bind(&end);
4878 }
4879 
4880 void Assembler::CheckVeneerPool(bool force_emit, bool require_jump,
4881  size_t margin) {
4882  // There is nothing to do if there are no pending veneer pool entries.
4883  if (unresolved_branches_.empty()) {
4884  DCHECK_EQ(next_veneer_pool_check_, kMaxInt);
4885  return;
4886  }
4887 
4888  DCHECK(pc_offset() < unresolved_branches_first_limit());
4889 
4890  // Some short sequence of instruction mustn't be broken up by veneer pool
4891  // emission, such sequences are protected by calls to BlockVeneerPoolFor and
4892  // BlockVeneerPoolScope.
4893  if (is_veneer_pool_blocked()) {
4894  DCHECK(!force_emit);
4895  return;
4896  }
4897 
4898  if (!require_jump) {
4899  // Prefer emitting veneers protected by an existing instruction.
4900  margin *= kVeneerNoProtectionFactor;
4901  }
4902  if (force_emit || ShouldEmitVeneers(margin)) {
4903  EmitVeneers(force_emit, require_jump, margin);
4904  } else {
4905  next_veneer_pool_check_ =
4906  unresolved_branches_first_limit() - kVeneerDistanceCheckMargin;
4907  }
4908 }
4909 
4910 int Assembler::buffer_space() const {
4911  return static_cast<int>(reloc_info_writer.pos() - pc_);
4912 }

4914 void Assembler::RecordConstPool(int size) {
4915  // We only need this for debugger support, to correctly compute offsets in the
4916  // code.
4917  Assembler::BlockPoolsScope block_pools(this);
4918  RecordRelocInfo(RelocInfo::CONST_POOL, static_cast<intptr_t>(size));
4919 }

4921 void PatchingAssembler::PatchAdrFar(int64_t target_offset) {
4922  // The code at the current instruction should be:
4923  // adr rd, 0
4924  // nop (adr_far)
4925  // nop (adr_far)
4926  // movz scratch, 0
4927 
4928  // Verify the expected code.
4929  Instruction* expected_adr = InstructionAt(0);
4930  CHECK(expected_adr->IsAdr() && (expected_adr->ImmPCRel() == 0));
4931  int rd_code = expected_adr->Rd();
4932  for (int i = 0; i < kAdrFarPatchableNNops; ++i) {
4933  CHECK(InstructionAt((i + 1) * kInstrSize)->IsNop(ADR_FAR_NOP));
4934  }
4935  Instruction* expected_movz =
4936  InstructionAt((kAdrFarPatchableNInstrs - 1) * kInstrSize);
4937  CHECK(expected_movz->IsMovz() && (expected_movz->ImmMoveWide() == 0) &&
4938  (expected_movz->ShiftMoveWide() == 0));
4939  int scratch_code = expected_movz->Rd();
4940 
4941  // Patch to load the correct address.
4942  Register rd = Register::XRegFromCode(rd_code);
4943  Register scratch = Register::XRegFromCode(scratch_code);
4944  // Addresses are only 48 bits.
4945  adr(rd, target_offset & 0xFFFF);
4946  movz(scratch, (target_offset >> 16) & 0xFFFF, 16);
4947  movk(scratch, (target_offset >> 32) & 0xFFFF, 32);
4948  DCHECK_EQ(target_offset >> 48, 0);
4949  add(rd, rd, scratch);
4950 }
4951 
4952 void PatchingAssembler::PatchSubSp(uint32_t immediate) {
4953  // The code at the current instruction should be:
4954  // sub sp, sp, #0
4955 
4956  // Verify the expected code.
4957  Instruction* expected_adr = InstructionAt(0);
4958  CHECK(expected_adr->IsAddSubImmediate());
4959  sub(sp, sp, immediate);
4960 }
